	(135, '==Further reading==\\n*Lebrecht, Norman: \'\'When the Music Stops: Managers, Maestros and the Corporate Murder of Classical Music\'\', Simon & Schuster 1996\\n*Imhorst, Christian: [http:\\/\\/www.imhorst.net\\/?page_id=21 The \\u2018Lost Generation\\u2019 of the Music Industry], published under the terms of the [[GNU Free Documentation License]] 2004\\n*Gerd Leonhard: \'\'Music Like Water \\u2013 the inevitable music ecosystem\'\'\\n*The Methods Reporter: [http:\\/\\/www.methodsreporter.com\\/2007\\/01\\/07\\/recording-industry-music-download-lawsuit\\/ Music Industry Misses Mark with Wrongful Suits]\\n*[http:\\/\\/www.soc.duke.edu\\/~s142tm01\\/main.html Music CD Industry] \\u2013 a mid-2000 overview put together by Duke University undergraduate students\\n* d\\u2019Angelo, Mario: \'\'Does globalisation mean ineluctable concentration ?\'\' in The Music Industry in the New Economy, Report of the Asia-Europe Seminar, Lyon, Oct. 25\\u201328, 2001, IEP de Lyon\\/Asia-Europe Foundation\\/Eurical, Editors Roche F., Marcq B., Colom\\u00e9 D., 2002, pp.&nbsp;53\\u201354.\\n* d\'Angelo, Mario: \'\'Perspectives of the Management of Musical Institutions in Europe\'\', OMF, Musical Activities and Institutions Sery, ParisIV-Sorbonne University, Ed. Musicales Aug. Zurfluh, Bourg-la-Reine, 2006.\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.competition-commission.org.uk\\/rep_pub\\/reports\\/1994\\/356recordedmusic.htm#full The supply of recorded music]: A report on the supply in the UK of prerecorded compact discs, vinyl discs and tapes containing music. Competition Commission, 1994.\\n* Tschmuck, Peter: \'\'Creativity and Innovation in the Music Industry\'\', Springer 2006.\\n* Ulrich Dolata: \'\'The Music Industry and the Internet. A Decade of Disruptive and Uncontrolled Sectoral Change\'\'. Research Contributions to Organizational Sociology and Innovation Studies. Discussion Paper 2011-02. [http:\\/\\/www.uni-stuttgart.de\\/soz\\/oi\\/publikationen\\/soi2_dolata_music_industry.pdf full text online]'),
	(136, '==External links==\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.newyorkmetro.com\\/nymetro\\/news\\/media\\/columns\\/medialife\\/6099\\/ New York Metro article by Michael Wolff analyzing the decline of the record industry]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.salon.com\\/tech\\/feature\\/2000\\/06\\/14\\/love\\/ Salon article on Courtney Love\'s criticism of record industry business practices]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.ftc.gov\\/opa\\/2002\\/06\\/3tenors.htm Federal Trade Commission press release regarding price fixing]\\n* [http:\\/\\/ag.state.nv.us\\/agpress\\/2002\\/02_0930b.pdf Antitrust settlement in Nevada price-fixing case]\\n* Songwriter [[Janis Ian]]\'s [http:\\/\\/www.janisian.com\\/reading\\/internet.php critique of the record industry\'s policies]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.mp3newswire.net\\/stories\\/5002\\/longshadows.html The Net is the Independent Artist\'s Radio] \\u2013 August 10, 2005 [[MP3 Newswire]] article\\n* \'\'[http:\\/\\/hbswk.hbs.edu\\/item.jhtml?id=4206&t=innovation Music Downloads: Pirates- or Customers?]\'\'. Silverthorne, Sean. [[Harvard Business School|Harvard Business School Working Knowledge]], 2004.\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.bl.uk\\/bipc\\/pdfs\\/Music_Industry_Guide.pdf The British Library - Music Industry Guide (sources of information)]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.ascap.com\\/resource\\/resource-4.html The ASCAP Resource Guide: Recording Industry]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.bpi.co.uk\\/music-business\\/article\\/structure-of-the-business.aspx BPI: Music business \\u2013 Industry Structure]\\n* [http:\\/\\/www.thembj.org Academic articles about the music industry] The Music Business Journal'),
	(137, '{{infobox Organization\\n|name         = National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences\\n|image        = National Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences, Pico & 34th, Los Angeles.JPG\\n|image_border = \\n|size         = 200px\\n|caption      = NARAS\' former Santa Monica Headquarters on [[Pico Boulevard]] & 34th Street\\n|map          = \\n|msize        = \\n|mcaption     = \\n|abbreviation = NARAS\\n|motto        = \\n|formation    = 1957\\n|extinction   = \\n|type         = music organization\\n|status       = \\n|purpose      = \\n|headquarters = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]], [[California]], USA\\n|location     = 3030 [[Olympic Boulevard (Los Angeles)|Olympic Blvd]].<br>[[Santa Monica]], California 90404\\n|region_served =\\n|membership   =  \\n|language     = English\\n|leader_title = President\\n|leader_name  = [[Neil Portnow]]\\n|main_organ = \\n|parent_organization = \\n|affiliations = [[MusiCares]]<br>Grammy Foundation<br>[[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences]]\\n|num_staff    = \\n|num_volunteers =\\n|budget       = \\n|website      = [http:\\/\\/www.grammy.org\\/ www.grammy.org]\\n|remarks =\\n}}'),
	(138, '\'\'\'The National Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences, Inc.\'\'\', known variously as \'\'\'The Recording Academy\'\'\' or \'\'\'NARAS\'\'\', is a [[U.S.]] organization of [[musicians]], [[Record producer|producers]], [[recording engineer]]s and other recording professionals dedicated to improving the quality of life and cultural condition for music and its makers. NARAS is headquartered in [[Los Angeles]]. [[Neil Portnow]] is the current president of The Academy. '),
	(139, 'The Recording Academy, which began in 1957, is famous for its [[Grammy Awards]]. In 1997, the Recording Academy launched [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences|The Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences, Inc.]], which produces the [[Latin Grammy Awards]].'),
	(140, '==History==\\nThe origin of the Academy dates back to the beginning of the 1950s [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] project. The Hollywood Chamber of Commerce asked the help of major recording industry executives in compiling a list of people in the music business who should be honored by Walk of Fame stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/projects.latimes.com\\/hollywood\\/star-walk\\/about\\/|title=Hollywood Walk of Fame History|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=21 May 2011}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.walkoffame.com\\/pages\\/history|title=Hollywood Walk of Fame History|publisher=Hollywood Walk of Fame|accessdate=21 May 2011}}<\\/ref>  The music committee, made up of these executives, compiled a list, but as they worked, they realized there were many more talented industry people who would not qualify to be recognized with a Hollywood Boulevard bronze star. This was the start of the Academy and also of the [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/news.google.com\\/newspapers?id=NnRPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5wQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1440,1446700&dq=paul+weston&hl=en|title=Record Academy Plans TV Spectacular Of Its Own|author=Thomas, Bob|date=8 April 1959|publisher=Ocala Star-Banner|accessdate=29 January 2011}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/news.google.com\\/newspapers?id=ca9NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cEgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7065,1739274&dq=paul+weston&hl=en|title=Recording Stars Plan Eddie To Join Oscar And Emmy|date=9 August 1957|publisher=The Deseret News|accessdate=2 February 2011}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/news.google.com\\/newspapers?id=aSBAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z1gMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3612,4838071&dq=paul+weston+grammy&hl=en|title=Bronze Stars Begot Grammy|date=22 February 1976|publisher=The Robesonian|accessdate=2 May 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(141, 'The Academy has twelve chapters in various locations in the [[United States]]. The twelve chapters are; [[Atlanta]], [[Chicago]], [[Florida]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Memphis]], [[Nashville]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Pacific Northwest]], [[Philadelphia]], [[San Francisco]], [[Texas]] and [[Washington D.C.]]'),
	(142, '== See also ==\\n* [[List of music organizations in the United States]]\\n* [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences]]\\n* [[Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]'),
	(143, '{"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"United_States","to":"United States"}],"pages":{"3434750":{"pageid":3434750,"ns":0,"title":"United States","revisions":[{"*":"{{Hatnote|This article is about the United States of America. For other uses of terms redirecting here, see [[US (disambiguation)]], [[USA (disambiguation)]], and [[United States (disambiguation)]].}}\\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}{{pp-move-indef}}\\n{{Infobox country\\n|conventional_long_name = United States of America\\n|common_name            = the United States\\n|image_flag             = Flag_of_the_United_States_(Pantone).svg\\n|image_coat             = US-GreatSeal-Obverse.svg\\n|length                 = 1776\\u2013present\\n|symbol_type            = Great Seal\\n|national_motto         = <!--Please read the talk page before editing these mottos:-->[[In God We Trust]]{{spaces|2}}<small>(official)<\\/small><br \\/>{{lang|la|\'\'[[E pluribus unum|E Pluribus Unum]]\'\'}}{{spaces|2}}<small>(traditional)<\\/small><br \\/><small>([[Latin]]: Out of Many, One)<\\/small>\\n|image_map              = USA orthographic.svg\\n|map_width              = 220px\\n|national_anthem        = [[File:Star Spangled Banner instrumental.ogg]]<br \\/>\\"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\\"\\n|official_languages     = None at federal level{{Ref label|engoffbox|a|}}\\n|languages_type         = [[National language]]\\n|languages              = [[English language|English]] (\'\'[[de facto]]\'\'){{Ref label|engfactobox|b|}}\\n|capital                = [[Washington, D.C.]]\\n|largest_city           = [[New York City]]\\n|latd                   = 38|latm=53|latNS=N|longd=77|longm=01|longEW=W\\n|government_type        = [[Federalism|Federal]] [[Presidential system|presidential]] [[constitutional republic]]\\n|leader_title1          = [[President of the United States|President]]\\n|leader_name1           = [[Barack Obama]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\\n|leader_title2          = [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]