	(300, 'Historically, the \\"Oscarcast\\" has pulled in a bigger haul when box-office hits are favored to win the Best Picture trophy. More than 57.25 million viewers tuned to the telecast for the [[70th Academy Awards]] in 1998, the year of \'\'[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]\'\', which generated close to US$600 million at the North American box office pre-Oscars.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http:\\/\\/seattletimes.nwsource.com\\/html\\/businesstechnology\\/2004196530_oscarads23.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Academy\'s red carpet big stage for advertisers | first=Meg | last=James | date=February 23, 2008}}<\\/ref> The [[76th Academy Awards]] ceremony in which \'\'[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]\'\' (pre-telecast box office earnings of US$368 million) received 11 Awards including Best Picture drew 43.56 million viewers.<ref name=\\"usatoday_oscar\\">{{Cite news | url=http:\\/\\/www.usatoday.com\\/life\\/movies\\/movieawards\\/oscars\\/2005-01-26-oscar-telecast_x.htm|work=USA Today |title=Oscars lack blockbuster to lure TV viewers | date=January 26, 2005 | first=Scott | last=Bowles | accessdate=November 8, 2006}}<\\/ref> The most watched ceremony based on [[Nielsen ratings]] to date, however, was the [[42nd Academy Awards]] (Best Picture \'\'[[Midnight Cowboy]]\'\') which drew a 43.4% household rating on April 7, 1970.<ref>[http:\\/\\/www.variety.com\\/index.asp?layout=chart_pass&charttype=chart_topshowsalltime Charts and Data: Top 100 TV Shows of All Time by \'\'Variety\'\']<\\/ref>'),
	(301, '[[Grauman\'s Chinese Theater]] in Hollywood then hosted the awards from 1944 to 1946, followed by the [[Shrine Auditorium]] in Los Angeles from 1947 to 1948. The [[21st Academy Awards]] in 1949 were held at the Academy Award Theater at what was the Academy\'s headquarters on [[Melrose Avenue]] in Hollywood.<ref>{{Cite web\\n  |url = http:\\/\\/www.oscars.org\\/aboutacademyawards\\/venues.html\\n  |title = Oscars Award Venues\\n  |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences\\n  |accessdate = April 13, 2007\\n  |archiveurl = http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20061212063803\\/http:\\/\\/www.oscars.org\\/aboutacademyawards\\/venues.html  |archivedate = December 12, 2006}}<\\/ref>'),
	(302, 'From 1950 to 1960, the awards were presented at Hollywood\'s [[Pantages Theatre (Hollywood)|Pantages Theatre]].  With the advent of television, the 1953\\u20131957 awards took place simultaneously in Hollywood and New York first at the NBC International Theatre (1953) and then at the NBC Century Theatre (1954\\u20131957), after which the ceremony took place solely in Los Angeles.  The Oscars moved to the [[Santa Monica Civic Auditorium]] in [[Santa Monica, California]] in 1961. By 1969, the Academy decided to move the ceremonies back to Los Angeles, this time to the [[Dorothy Chandler Pavilion]] at the [[Los Angeles Music Center|Los Angeles County Music Center]].'),
	(303, '{{col-begin}}\\n{{col-break}}\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]: 1936 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]: 1936 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Film]]: 2001 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Animated Short Film]]: 1931 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]: 1948 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Documentary|Best Documentary Feature]]: 1943 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Short|Best Documentary Short]]: 1941 to present\\n{{col-break}}\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]]: 1935 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]: 1947 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Film]]: 1931 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Makeup|Best Makeup]]: 1981 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]]: 1934 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]: 1934 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]]: 1963 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Sound|Best Sound Mixing]]: 1930 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]: 1939 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]: 1928 to present\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]: 1940 to present\\n{{col-end}}'),
	(304, 'Another award, entitled the [[Academy Award for Best Original Musical]], is still in the Academy rulebooks and has yet to be retired.  However, due to continuous insufficient eligibility each year, it has not been awarded since 1984 (when \'\'[[Purple Rain (film)|Purple Rain]]\'\' won).<ref>http:\\/\\/www.oscars.org\\/awards\\/academyawards\\/rules\\/rule16.html<\\/ref>'),
	(305, '{{col-begin}}\\n{{col-break}}\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Assistant Director|Best Assistant Director]]: 1933 to 1937\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Dance Direction|Best Dance Direction]]: 1935 to 1937\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Engineering Effects|Best Engineering Effects]]: 1928 only\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Original Musical or Comedy Score|Best Original Musical or Comedy Score]]: 1995 to 1999\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Story|Best Original Story]]: 1928 to 1956\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Score \\u2013 Adaptation or Treatment|Best Score \\u2013 Adaptation or Treatment]]: 1962 to 1969; 1973\\n{{col-break}}\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Short Film - Color|Best Short Film \\u2013 Color]]: 1936 and 1937\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Short Film - Live Action - 2 Reels|Best Short Film \\u2013 Live Action \\u2013 2 Reels]]: 1936 to 1956\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Short Film - Novelty|Best Short Film \\u2013 Novelty]]: 1932 to 1935\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Title Writing|Best Title Writing]]: 1928 only\\n* [[Academy Award for Best Unique and Artistic Production|Best Unique and Artistic Quality of Production]]: 1928 only\\n{{col-end}}'),
	(306, '* [[Academy Honorary Award]]: 1929 to present\\n* [[Academy Scientific and Technical Award]]: 1931 to present\\n* [[Gordon E. Sawyer Award]]: 1981 to present\\n* [[Jean Hersholt Humanitarian Award]]: 1956 to present\\n* [[Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award]]: 1938 to present'),
