	(409, '==Artists with multiple nominations and awards==\\t\\nThe following artists received multiple nominations:\\t\\n*Seven: [[Kanye West]]\\t\\n*Six: [[Adele (singer)|Adele]], [[Bruno Mars]], [[Foo Fighters]]\\t\\t\\n*Five: [[Lil Wayne]], [[Radiohead]], [[Skrillex]]\\t\\t\\n*Four: [[Bon Iver]], [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Mumford & Sons]], [[Nicki Minaj]],  [[Rihanna]]\\n*Three: [[Blake Shelton]], [[Brandon Heath]], [[Cee Lo Green]], [[Chris Brown (American entertainer)|Chris Brown]], [[Chris Tomlin]], [[Coldplay]], [[Deadmau5]], [[Jason Aldean]], [[Kelly Price]], [[Lady Gaga]], [[Ledisi]], [[Lupe Fiasco]], [[Taylor Swift]]\\n*Two: [[Alexandre Desplat]], [[Alison Krauss & Union Station]], [[Beyonc\\u00e9]], [[Charlie Wilson (singer)|Charlie Wilson]], [[Daft Punk]], [[David Guetta]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[Foster the People]], [[Gillian Welch]], [[Katy Perry]], [[Kenny Chesney]], [[Kirk Franklin]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Marsha Ambrosius]], [[Mary Mary]], [[Robyn]], [[R. Kelly]], [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Thompson Square]], [[The Civil Wars]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[\\"Weird Al\\" Yankovic]], [[Wiz Khalifa]]'),
	(410, '{"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Staples_Center","to":"Staples Center"}],"pages":{"516154":{"pageid":516154,"ns":0,"title":"Staples Center","revisions":[{"*":"{{Infobox Stadium\\n| stadium_name        = Staples Center\\n| nickname            =\\n| image               = [[File:Staples Center Logo.svg|210px]]<br \\/>[[Image:StaplesCenter051209.jpg|260px]]\\n| location = 1111 S. [[Figueroa Street]],<br \\/> [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], 90015\\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|34|2|35|N|118|16|2|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=it}}\\n| broke_ground        = March 31, 1998\\n| opened              = October 17, 1999\\n| owner               = L.A. Arena Company<br \\/>[[Anschutz Entertainment Group]]\\n| operator            = L.A. Arena Company<br \\/>[[Anschutz Entertainment Group]]\\n| construction_cost   = $375 Million [[United States dollar|USD]]<br \\/>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|375000000|1999}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})\\n| architect           = [[NBBJ]]\\n| structural engineer = John A Martin & Associates<ref>http:\\/\\/www.johnmartin.com\\/projects\\/sports--recreation.html<\\/ref>\\n| services engineer   = M*E Engineers Inc.\\n| general_contractor  = [[PCL Construction|PCL Construction Services, Inc.]]<ref>http:\\/\\/basketball.ballparks.com\\/NBA\\/LosAngelesClippers\\/newindex.htm<\\/ref>\\n| tenants             = [[Los Angeles Clippers]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\\u2013present)<br \\/>[[Los Angeles Lakers]] (NBA) (1999\\u2013present)<br \\/>[[Los Angeles Kings]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\\u2013present)<br \\/>[[Los Angeles Sparks]] ([[Women\'s National Basketball Association|WNBA]]) (2001\\u2013present)<br \\/>[[Los Angeles Avengers]] ([[Arena Football League (1987-2008)|AFL]]) (2000\\u20132008)<br \\/>[[Los Angeles D-Fenders]] ([[NBA Development League|D-League]]) (2006\\u20132010)\\n| seating_capacity      = [[Basketball]]: 19,060 (Clippers Games)<br \\/>18,997 (Lakers Games)<ref name = \\"staplescenterseating\\"\\/><br \\/>[[Ice hockey]]: 18,118<br \\/>[[Arena football]]: 16,096<br \\/>[[Concerts]]: 20,000<br \\/>[[Boxing]]\\/[[Wrestling]]: 21,000\\n}}\\n\'\'\'Staples Center\'\'\' is a multi-purpose [[arena|sports arena]] in [[Downtown Los Angeles|Downtown]] [[Los Angeles]]. Adjacent to the [[L.A. Live]] development, it is located next to the [[Los Angeles Convention Center]] complex along [[Figueroa Street]]. Opening on October 17, 1999, it is one of the major sporting facilities in the [[Greater Los Angeles Area]].'),
	(411, '==Description==\\n===Structure and architecture===\\nStaples Center measures {{convert|950,000|sqft|m2|1}} of total space, with a {{convert|94|ft|m|1|adj=on}} by {{convert|200|ft|m|1|adj=on}} arena floor. It stands {{convert|150|ft|m|1}} tall.<ref name = \\"LASportsCouncil\\"\\/> The arena seats up to 19,079 for [[basketball]], 18,118 for [[ice hockey]] and [[arena football]], and around 20,000 for [[concert]]s or other sporting events.<ref name = \\"staplescenterseating\\">{{Cite web|publisher=Staples Center|title=Guest Services: Seating Capacity|url= http:\\/\\/www.staplescenter.com\\/doublecol.php?section=guestservices&page=faqs#s|accessdate=2010-07-25}}<\\/ref><ref name = \\"AEGstaplescenter\\"\\/> Two-thirds of the arena\'s seating, including 2,500 club seats, are in the lower bowl. There are also 160 luxury suites, including 15 event suites, on three levels between the lower and upper bowls.<ref name = \\"LASportsCouncil\\"\\/> The arena\'s attendance record is held by the fight between World [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[Welterweight]] Champion, [[Antonio Margarito]] and [[Shane Mosley]] with a crowd of 20,820 set on January 25, 2009.<ref name = \\"LAT\\">{{Cite news| last = Dwyre | first = Bill | publisher = Los Angeles Times | title = Shane Mosley Shows He\'s Not Finished | url = http:\\/\\/www.latimes.com\\/sports\\/la-sp-dwyre-mosley-margarito25-2009jan25,0,5631662.column | date = 2009-01-25 | accessdate = 2009-01-25}}<\\/ref>\\n;Star Plaza\\nOutside the arena at the Star Plaza are statues of [[Wayne Gretzky]] and [[Magic Johnson]], although both sports legends played at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], where the Kings, Lakers and Sparks previously played. A third statue of boxer [[Oscar De La Hoya]] was unveiled outside Staples Center on December 1, 2008.<ref name = \\"LATimes-DeLaHoya\\">{{Cite news| last = Plaschke | first = Bill |title = Oscar De La Hoya Gets A Statue Of Limitations | url = http:\\/\\/www.latimes.com\\/sports\\/la-sp-plaschke2-2008dec02,0,3207891,full.column | publisher = Los Angeles Times | date = 2008-12-02 | accessdate = 2008-12-02}}<\\/ref> On April 20, 2010 a fourth statue of the late long time Lakers broadcaster [[Chick Hearn]], behind a Laker desk with a chair for fans to sit down for a picture, was unveiled. A fifth statue of the Laker legend [[Jerry West]] [[dribbling]] was unveiled on February 17, 2011.'),
	(412, '==History==\\n[[File:Staples Center Lakers.jpg|thumb|left|Staples Center in Los Angeles hosts the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] ([[NBA]]), [[Los Angeles Clippers]] ([[NBA]]), [[Los Angeles Kings]] ([[NHL]]), and [[Los Angeles Sparks]] ([[WNBA]]).]]\\nConstruction broke ground in 1998 and the Staples Center was opened a year later. It was financed privately at a cost of [[United States dollar|$]]375 million and is named for the office-supply company [[Staples, Inc.]], which was one of the center\'s corporate sponsors that paid for [[naming rights]].<ref name = \\"LASportsCouncil\\"\\/>'),
	(413, 'The arena opened on October 17, 1999, with a [[Bruce Springsteen]] & The [[E Street Band]] concert as its inaugural event. Since its opening day, it has hosted seven [[NBA Finals]] series, with the Lakers, three [[WNBA Finals]], the [[2000 Democratic National Convention]], the 2002 [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. Figure Skating Championships]], the [[52nd National Hockey League All-Star Game|52nd NHL All-Star game]], two [[NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Games]] (in [[2004 NBA All-Star Game|2004]] and [[2011 NBA All-Star Game|2011]]), the [[Pacific-10 Conference Men\'s Basketball Tournament]], since 2002, the [[WTA Tour Championships]], from 2002-2005, [[UFC 60]] in 2006, [[UFC 104]] in 2009, the inaugural [[Latin Grammy Awards]] in 2000, the annual [[Grammy Award]]s, since 2000, with the exception of 2003, the [[2009 World Figure Skating Championships]], the [[X Games|Summer X Games]] indoor competitions, since 2003, as well as numerous concerts and [[HBO Boxing|HBO Championship Boxing]] matches.<ref name = \\"AEGstaplescenter\\"\\/> In addition to hosting [[WrestleMania 21]], which held the venue\'s attendance record of 20,193 until it was surpassed in January 2009 by the 20,820 draw for the [[Shane Mosley]] vs [[Antonio Margarito]] Welterweight fight, it has also hosted [[Unforgiven (2002)|Unforgiven 2002]], [[Judgment Day (2004)|Judgment Day 2004]], [[No Way Out (2007)|No Way Out 2007]], and [[SummerSlam]] for three consecutive years since 2009 (soon to host the event for the fourth year), as well as other [[WWE]] events.<ref name = \\"TeamsEvents\\"\\/> The Los Angeles Kings, of the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] hosted the [[2010 NHL Entry Draft]] at the arena in June 2010.\\n[[Image:Staples Center LA Live.jpg|thumb|225px|Night view of Staples Center and L.A. Live]]\\nThe arena has hosted concerts by many famous artists, spanning many different genres. [[Mariah Carey]] kicked off the US leg of her [[Rainbow World Tour]] at the arena on March 16, 2000, this marked her first performance in the US, since 1993. [[Beyonc\\u00e9 Knowles|Beyonc\\u00e9]] performed at the Center during [[The Beyonc\\u00e9 Experience]] Tour on September 2, 2007, which was filmed and released as, \'\'[[The Beyonc\\u00e9 Experience Live]]\'\'. [[Taylor Swift]] performed at the arena during her [[Fearless Tour]] on May 22, 2009 and April 15\\u201316, 2010. [[John Mayer]] was a special guest at the May 22 show, together they performed \\"[[Your Body Is a Wonderland]]\\" and \\"White Horse\\".<ref name = \\"Mayer\\">{{Cite web|url=http:\\/\\/tonicgossip.com\\/2009\\/05\\/23\\/john-mayer-joins-taylor-swift-on-tour\\/|title=John Mayer Joins Taylor Swift on Tour|date=2009-05-23|publisher=Tonic Gossip|accessdate=2009-06-28}}<\\/ref> [[Michael Jackson]] rehearsed for his [[This Is It (Michael Jackson concerts)|This Is It]] concerts at the arena, before his [[Death of Michael Jackson|death]]. On July 7, 2009, a [[Michael Jackson memorial service|public memorial for Michael Jackson]] was held at Staples Center. [[K-pop]] talent agency [[SM Entertainment]] held its annual SM Town tour for the first time in America at the venue on September 4, 2010 which featured the likes of [[BoA]], [[TVXQ]], [[Super Junior]], [[Girls\' Generation]], [[SHINee]], and [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]] thus becoming the first Koreans ever to perform at the venue.'),
	(414, '[[File:ClippersStaples.JPG|thumb|225px|left|Staples Center before a Clippers game]]\\nOn January 22, 2006, Los Angeles Lakers player [[Kobe Bryant]] scored a career-high 81 points in the Staples Center against the [[Toronto Raptors]], the [[List of National Basketball Association players with 60 or more points in a game|second-highest number of points scored in a single game]] in NBA history,<ref name=\\"81-Point-Game Highlights\\">{{cite video |people=NBA Staff |title={{Youtube|id=FeXZY4eVLlo|title=Watch All of Kobe\'s 81 Points in 3 Minutes}} |publisher=[[NBA]] |date=2006-01-22 |accessdate=2008-12-06}}<\\/ref> second only to [[Wilt Chamberlain]]\'s [[Wilt Chamberlain\'s 100-point game|100-point performance]]. Of the team\'s five NBA championships since moving to the venue, the Lakers have celebrated their {{nbafy|2000}} and {{nbafy|2010}} victories at Staples Center with series-winning victories at home.'),
	(415, 'Prior to the [[2006-07 NBA season]], the lighting inside Staples Center was modified for Lakers games. The lights were focused only on the court itself (hence the promotional \'\'Lights Out\'\' campaign), reminiscent of the Lakers\' early years at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]]. Initial fan reaction was positive, and has been a fixture on home games since. The [[Daktronics]] see-through shot-clock was first installed prior to the [[2008-09 NBA season]]. The Clippers adopted the new see through shot clock prior to the [[2010-11 NBA season]]. For Sparks games, the court used is named after Sparks legend [[Lisa Leslie]], and was officially named prior to the 2009 home opener against the [[Detroit Shock|Shock]] on June 6, 2009.'),
	(416, 'During the late summer of 2010, modifications were made to the arena, including refurbished locker rooms for the Clippers, Kings, and Lakers and the installation of a new high-definition center-hung video scoreboard, replacing the original one that had been in place since the building opened in 1999.<ref name = \\"Live4HD\\"> {{Cite news|title = Staples Center unveils Live 4HD scoreboard system by Panasonic | url = http:\\/\\/www.staplescenter.com\\/doublecol.php?section=about&page=news_article&news_id=942 | publisher = staplescenter.com | date = 2010-09-22 | accessdate = 2010-10-18}} <\\/ref> The [[Panasonic]] Live 4HD scoreboard was officially unveiled on September 22nd, as AEG and Staples Center executives, as well as player representatives from the Clippers ([[Craig Smith (basketball)|Craig Smith]]), Kings ([[Matt Greene]]), and Lakers ([[Sasha Vujacic]]) were on hand for the presentation.'),
	(417, '==Image gallery==\\n<center> <gallery perrow=\\"6\\">\\nImage:Staples Center Panorama.jpg|Staples Center as seen from [[Nokia Plaza]]\\nImage:Staples Center satellite view.png|Satellite view of Staples Center prior to the L.A. Live development\\nImage:LA_Kings_2010.jpg|Staples Center during a Los Angeles Kings game\\n<\\/gallery><\\/center>'),
