	(440, '{{wide image|Los angeles mountains to ocean pano.jpg|1900px|<center>Panorama of Los Angeles as viewed from [[Mulholland Drive]]. Left to right: [[Santa Ana Mountains]], downtown, Hollywood (foreground), [[Wilshire Boulevard]], [[Port of Los Angeles]], [[Palos Verdes Peninsula]], [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Santa Catalina Island]], and [[Los Angeles International Airport]].<\\/center>}}\\n[[Image:Hollywood boulevard from kodak theatre.jpg|thumb|Hollywood, a well-known district of Los Angeles, is often mistaken for an independent city (as [[West Hollywood]] is).]]'),
	(441, 'The city is divided into over 80 districts and neighborhoods,<ref>{{cite news | url = http:\\/\\/www.latimes.com\\/news\\/local\\/la-me-map19-2009feb19,0,5915275.story | title = L.A. neighborhoods, you\'re on the map |work=Los Angeles Times | date = 19 February 2009 | accessdate =2 October 2011 | first=Bob | last=Pool}}<\\/ref> many of which were [[incorporated place]]s or [[unincorporated area|communities]] that were annexed by the city.<ref name=\\"Abu-Lughod1999\\">{{cite book|last=Abu-Lughod|first=Janet L.|authorlink=Janet L. Abu-Lughod|title=New York, Chicago, Los Angeles: America\'s global cities|url=http:\\/\\/books.google.com\\/books?id=rrLlt1k59voC&pg=PA66|accessdate=2 October 2011|year=1999|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-0-8166-3336-4|page=66}}<\\/ref>  [[Greater Los Angeles Area|Greater Los Angeles]] includes a number of enclaves and nearby communities. Generally, the city is divided into the following areas: Downtown Los Angeles, [[East Los Angeles (region)|East Los Angeles]] and [[Northeast Los Angeles]], [[South Los Angeles]], the [[Harbor Area]], [[Greater Hollywood, Los Angeles|Greater Hollywood]], [[Wilshire, Los Angeles|Wilshire]], the [[Westside (Los Angeles County)|Westside]], and the San Fernando and [[Crescenta Valley]]s.'),
	(442, 'Some well-known communities within Los Angeles include [[West Adams, Los Angeles|West Adams]], [[Watts, Los Angeles|Watts]], [[Leimert Park, Los Angeles|Leimert Park]], [[Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles|Baldwin Hills]], [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice]], the [[Financial District, Los Angeles|Downtown Financial District]], [[Los Feliz, Los Angeles|Los Feliz]], [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles|Silver Lake]], Hollywood, [[Koreatown, Los Angeles|Koreatown]], [[Westwood, Los Angeles|Westwood]] and the more affluent areas of [[Bel Air, Los Angeles|Bel Air]], [[Benedict Canyon, Los Angeles|Benedict Canyon]], [[Hollywood Hills]], [[Hancock Park, Los Angeles|Hancock Park]], [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]], [[Century City, Los Angeles|Century City]], and [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].'),
	(443, 'Important landmarks in Los Angeles include [[Walt Disney Concert Hall]], the [[Kodak Theatre]], the [[Griffith Observatory]], the [[Getty Center]], the [[Getty Villa]], the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]], the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], [[Grauman\'s Chinese Theatre]], the [[Hollywood Sign]], the [[Bradbury Building]], [[Hollywood Boulevard]], the [[Capitol Records Building]], [[Los Angeles City Hall]], the [[Hollywood Bowl]], the [[Theme Building]], the [[Watts Towers]], [[Staples Center]], [[Dodger Stadium]], and [[Nuestra Se\\u00f1ora Reina de los Angeles Asistencia|La Placita Olvera]]\\/[[Olvera Street]].'),
	(444, 'Los Angeles is home to Hollywood, globally recognized as the epicenter of the motion picture industry. A testament to its preeminence in film, the city plays host to the annual [[Academy Awards]], the oldest and one of the most prominent award ceremonies in the world. Finally, Los Angeles is home to the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]], the oldest [[film school]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sharon|last=Waxman|url=http:\\/\\/www.nytimes.com\\/2006\\/01\\/31\\/movies\\/31film.html|title= At U.S.C., a Practical Emphasis in Film | publisher = New York Times|date= 31 January 2006 | accessdate = 14 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(445, 'The performing arts play a major role in Los Angeles\' cultural identity. According to the USC Stevens Institute for Innovation, \\"there are more than 1,100 annual theatrical productions and 21 openings every week.\\"<ref name=\\"Only In LA\\"\\/> The [[Los Angeles Music Center]] is \\"one of the three largest performing arts centers in the nation,\\" with more than 1.3 million visitors per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.musiccenter.org\\/visit\\/index.html |title=Explore the Center |publisher=Music Center of Los Angeles County|accessdate=14 October 2011}}<\\/ref> The [[Walt Disney Concert Hall]], centerpiece of the Music Center, is home to the prestigious [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]]. Notable organizations such as [[Center Theatre Group]], the [[Los Angeles Master Chorale]], and the [[Los Angeles Opera]] are also resident companies of the Music Center. Talent is locally cultivated at premier institutions such as the [[Colburn School]] and the [[USC Thornton School of Music]].'),
	(446, '\\n===Museums and galleries===\\n{{See also|List of museums in California#Los Angeles|l1=Los Angeles City Museums}}\\nThere are 841 museums and art galleries in [[Los Angeles County]].<ref name=lmu>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.lmu.edu\\/about\\/The_Los_Angeles_Region.htm |title=The Los Angeles Region |publisher=Loyola Marymount University |date=5 May 2008 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}<\\/ref> In fact, Los Angeles has more museums per capita than any other city in the world.<ref name=lmu \\/> Some of the notable museums are the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (the largest art museum in the Western United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.lacma.org\\/overview|publisher=LACMA|title=Overview|accessdate=20 October 2011}}<\\/ref>), the [[Getty Center]] (part of the larger [[J. Paul Getty Trust]], the world\'s wealthiest art institution<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Los Angeles Times|date = 16 March 2009|last=Boehm|first=Mike|title=Getty slashes operating budget after severe investment losses|url=http:\\/\\/articles.latimes.com\\/2009\\/mar\\/16\\/entertainment\\/et-getty16|accessdate=20 October 2011}}<\\/ref>), and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]]. A significant number of art galleries are located on [[Gallery Row]], and tens of thousands attend the monthly Downtown Art Walk there.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Los Angeles Times|url=http:\\/\\/articles.latimes.com\\/2011\\/aug\\/05\\/local\\/la-me-0805-art-walk-20110805|date=5 August 2011|first=Kate|last=Mather|title=Downtown L.A. Art Walk safety changes planned|accessdate=20 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(447, '===Media===\\n{{Main|Media in Los Angeles}}\\n{{See also|List of television shows set in Los Angeles|List of films set in Los Angeles}}\\n[[Image:Foxyplaza.jpg|thumb|The [[Fox Plaza (Los Angeles)|Fox Plaza]] in [[Century City, Los Angeles|Century City]], headquarters for [[20th Century Fox]], is a major financial district for [[West Los Angeles]]]]'),
	(448, 'The major daily English-language newspaper in the area is the \'\'[[Los Angeles Times]]\'\'. \'\'[[La Opini\\u00f3n]]\'\' is the city\'s major daily Spanish-language paper, and \'\'[[The Korea Times (Los Angeles)|The Korea Times]]\'\' is the city\'s major daily Korean-language paper. \'\'[[Investor\'s Business Daily]]\'\' is distributed from its L.A. corporate offices, which are headquartered in Playa Del Rey. There are also a number of smaller regional newspapers, alternative weeklies and magazines, including the \'\'[[Los Angeles Daily News|Daily News]]\'\' (which focuses coverage on the [[San Fernando Valley]]), \'\'[[LA Weekly]],\'\' \'\'[[Los Angeles CityBeat]],\'\' \'\'[[L.A. Record]]\'\' (which focuses coverage on the music scene in the [[Greater Los Angeles Area]]), \'\'Los Angeles\'\' magazine, \'\'[[Los Angeles Business Journal]],\'\' \'\'Los Angeles Daily Journal\'\' (legal industry paper), \'\'[[The Hollywood Reporter]]\'\' and \'\'[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]\'\' (entertainment industry papers), and \'\'[[Los Angeles Downtown News]].\'\' In addition to the major papers, numerous local periodicals serve immigrant communities in their native languages, including Armenian, English, Korean, Persian, Russian, Chinese, Japanese, Hebrew, and Arabic. Many cities adjacent to Los Angeles also have their own daily newspapers whose coverage and availability overlaps into certain Los Angeles neighborhoods. Examples include \'\'[[Daily Breeze|The Daily Breeze]]\'\' (serving the [[South Bay, Los Angeles|South Bay]]), and \'\'[[Long Beach Press-Telegram|The Long Beach Press-Telegram]].\'\''),
	(449, 'The city has major broadcast channels as well as three [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] stations. World TV operates on two channels and the area has several Spanish-language television networks. [[KTBN]] 40 is the [[flagship station]] of the religious [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]], based out of [[Santa Ana, California|Santa Ana]]. A variety of independent television stations also operate in the area.'),
	(450, '===Sports===\\n[[Image:Dodger Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[Dodger Stadium]] is the home of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]]]\\n{{See also|Sports in Los Angeles|History of the National Football League in Los Angeles}}\\nLos Angeles is the home of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] of [[Major League Baseball]], the [[Los Angeles Kings]] of the [[National Hockey League]], the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] and [[Los Angeles Lakers]] of the [[National Basketball Association]], the [[Los Angeles D-Fenders]], an NBA Development team owned by the Los Angeles Lakers, and the [[Los Angeles Sparks]] of the [[Women\'s National Basketball Association]]. Los Angeles is also home to the [[USC Trojans]] and the [[UCLA Bruins]] in the NCAA, both of which are [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] teams in the [[Pacific-12 Conference]]. The [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] and [[C.D. Chivas USA|Club Deportivo Chivas USA]] of [[Major League Soccer]] are based in [[Carson, California|Carson]].'),
	(451, 'Los Angeles is the second-largest city and [[media market|television market]] in the United States, but has no [[NFL]] team. the nearest team is located in [[San Diego]] and are called the [[San Diego Chargers|Chargers]]. At one time Los Angeles had two NFL teams, the [[St. Louis Rams|Rams]] and the [[Oakland Raiders|Raiders]]. Both left the city in 1995, with the Rams moving to [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] and the Raiders heading back to their original home of [[Oakland, California|Oakland]].  Prior to 1995, the Rams called Memorial Coliseum home (1946\\u20131979) and the Raiders played their home games at Memorial Coliseum from 1982 to 1994.\\n[[Image:StaplesCenter051209.jpg|thumb|[[Staples Center]], a premier venue for sports and entertainment, is home to five professional sports teams, most notably the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]]]'),
	(452, 'Since the franchise\'s departures the NFL as an organization, and individual NFL owners, have attempted to relocate a team to the city. Immediately following the 1995 NFL season, [[Seattle Seahawks]] owner [[Ken Behring]] went as far as packing up moving vans to start play in the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] under a new team name and logo for the 1996 season. The [[Washington (state)|State of Washington]] filed a lawsuit to prevent the move.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Business Wire|url=http:\\/\\/findarticles.com\\/p\\/articles\\/mi_m0EIN\\/is_1996_Feb_2\\/ai_17922281|title=Seattle Seahawks owner Ken Behring announces move of NFL franchise|date=2 February 1996|accessdate=22 October 2011}}<\\/ref> In 2003, then-NFL Commissioner [[Paul Tagliabue]] said that he thought that Los Angeles would get a new [[expansion team]], a thirty-third franchise, after the choice of Houston over Los Angeles in the 2002 league expansion round.<ref>{{cite news|last=Satzman|first=Darrell|work=Los Angeles Business Journal|url=http:\\/\\/findarticles.com\\/p\\/articles\\/mi_m5072\\/is_4_25\\/ai_97616093 |title=NFL\'s interest in returning to Los Angeles long on desire, far from reality \\u2013 Up Front|date=27 January 2003|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20040925035748\\/http:\\/\\/www.findarticles.com\\/p\\/articles\\/mi_m5072\\/is_4_25\\/ai_97616093|archivedate=25 September 2004 | accessdate = 22 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Despite these efforts, and the failure to build a new stadium for an NFL team, Los Angeles is still expected to return to the league through expansion or relocation. On August 9, 2011 the LA City Council approved plans to build [[Farmers Field]], which will become home to an NFL team in the future. The stadium is expected to be completed by 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/latimesblogs.latimes.com\\/lanow\\/2011\\/08\\/nfl-stadium-los-angeles.html |title=L.A. NFL stadium agreement approved by City Council on 12-0 vote - latimes.com |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=9 August 2011 |accessdate=22 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(453, 'Los Angeles has twice played host to the Summer Olympic Games, in [[1932 Summer Olympics|1932]] and in [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984]]. When the tenth Olympic Games were hosted in 1932, the former 10th Street was renamed Olympic Blvd. Super Bowls I and VII were also held in the city as well as multiple [[FIFA World Cup]] games in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] including the [[1994 FIFA World Cup Final|final]]. Los Angeles will host the [[Special Olympics World Games|Special Olympics World Summer Games]] in [[2015 Special Olympics World Summer Games|2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.specialolympics.org\\/2011\\/2011-09-14__Los_Angeles_to_Host_2015_Special_Olympics_World_Summer_Games.aspx |title=Los Angeles To Host 2015 Special Olympics World Summer Games |publisher=Special Olympics |date=14 September 2011 |accessdate=22 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(454, 'Los Angeles also boasts a number of sports venues, including [[Dodger Stadium]], [[Los Angeles Coliseum]], [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], [[Staples Center]], a sports and entertainment complex that also hosts concerts and awards shows such as the Grammys. Staples Center also serves as the home arena for the Los Angeles Clippers and Los Angeles Lakers of the NBA, the Los Angeles Sparks of the WNBA, and the Los Angeles Kings of the NHL. It was also home to the Los Angeles Avengers of the original [[Arena Football League|AFL]], a team that did not participate in that league\'s ongoing revival.'),
	(455, 'The [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] of [[Major League Baseball]] and the [[Anaheim Ducks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] are in the Los Angeles media market and are based in [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]] in Orange County. The Angels began as an expansion franchise team in Los Angeles in 1961 and played at Los Angeles\' [[Wrigley Field (Los Angeles)|Wrigley Field]] and then Dodger Stadium before moving to Anaheim in 1966.<ref name=iron>{{Cite book  | last =Leonard Pitt, Dale Pitt | title =Los Angeles A to Z | publisher=[[University of California Press]]  | year =1997  | pages =560\\u2013561  | isbn =0520205308}}<\\/ref> The Ducks, who have played in Anaheim since their inception as an expansion team in {{nhly|1993|start}}, were originally owned by [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] and known as the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, after [[The Mighty Ducks|the popular Disney film]]. The team adopted its current name in {{nhly|2006|start}}, a year after Disney sold the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/ducks.nhl.com\\/club\\/page.htm?id=44140 |title=Ducks History: The Ducks Look |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=22 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(456, '===Religion===\\n[[Image:Lacathedral.jpg|thumb|[[Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels]] is the mother cathedral for the Los Angeles archdiocese]]'),
	(457, 'The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles|Roman Catholic Archbishop of Los Angeles]] leads the largest [[Diocese|archdiocese]] in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pomfret|first=John|url=http:\\/\\/www.washingtonpost.com\\/wp-dyn\\/content\\/article\\/2006\\/04\\/01\\/AR2006040101206.html|title= Cardinal Puts Church in Fight for Immigration Rights|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=2 April 2006|accessdate=22 October 2011}}<\\/ref> [[Roger Mahony|Cardinal Roger Mahony]] oversaw construction of the [[Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels]], which opened in September, 2002 in downtown Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite journal|journal = Los Angeles Times | url = http:\\/\\/articles.latimes.com\\/2002\\/sep\\/04\\/local\\/me-cathedral4 | title = Pomp Past, Masses Flock to Cathedral | date = 4 September 2002 | accessdate = 22 October 2011 | last1 = Stammer | first1 = Larry B. | last2=Becerra | first2=Hector}}<\\/ref> Construction of the cathedral marked a coming of age of the city\'s Catholic, heavily Latino community. There are numerous Catholic churches and parishes throughout Los Angeles.'),
	(458, 'With 621,000 [[American Jews|Jews]] in the metropolitan area (490,000 in city proper), the region has the second largest population of Jews in the United States.<ref name=Jews>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.simpletoremember.com\\/vitals\\/world-jewish-population.htm |title=World Jewish Population |publisher=SimpleToRemember.com |accessdate=23 October 2011}}<\\/ref>  Many of Los Angeles\' Jews now live on the [[Westside, Los Angeles|Westside]] and in the [[San Fernando Valley]], though [[Boyle Heights, Los Angeles, California|Boyle Heights]] and [[Northwest Los Angeles]] once had large Jewish populations. Many varieties of Judaism are represented in the area, including [[Reform Judaism|Reform]], [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]], [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]], and [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Reconstructionist]]. The [[Breed Street Shul]] in [[East Los Angeles, California|East Los Angeles]], built in 1923, was the largest synagogue west of Chicago in its early decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/www.isjm.org\\/jhr\\/no1\\/america.htm|title=Washington Symposium and Exhibition Highlight Restoration and Adaptive Reuse of American Synagogues|work=Jewish Heritage Report|number= 1 |date=March 1997|accessdate = 23 October 2011}}<\\/ref> (It is no longer a sacred space and is being converted to a museum and community center.)<ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/www.isjm.org\\/jhr\\/IInos1-2\\/breedstreet.htm|title=Los Angeles\'s Breed Street Shul Saved by Politicians|work=Jewish Heritage Report |volume=II|number=1\\u20132 |date=Spring-Summer 1998|accessdate = 23 October 2011}}<\\/ref> The [[Kabbalah Centre]] also has a presence in the city.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http:\\/\\/www.time.com\\/time\\/magazine\\/article\\/0,9171,1223372,00.html | journal = Time Magazine | title = Madonna Finds A Cause | date = 6 August 2006 | last = Luscombe | first = Belinda |accessdate = 23 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(459, 'Los Angeles has had a rich and influential Protestant tradition.  The first Protestant service in Los Angeles was a Methodist meeting held in a private home in 1850 and the oldest Protestant church still operating was founded in 1867. In the early 1900s the [[Bible Institute Of Los Angeles]] published the founding documents of the [[Christian Fundamentalist]] movement and the [[Azusa Street Revival]] launched [[Pentecostalism]]. [[Aimee Semple McPherson]] broadcast over the radio in the 1920s from the [[Angelus Temple]], home of the [[International Church of the Foursquare Gospel]] and its [[Life Pacific College]]. The [[Potter\'s House Christian Fellowship]] and [[Metropolitan Community Church]] also had their origins in the city. [[Billy Graham]]\'s first big success came in L.A. and notable ministers connected to the city include [[Robert P. Shuler]], [[Charles E. Fuller]], [[Gene Scott]], [[Jesse Lee Peterson]], and [[Solomon Burke]]. Important churches in the city include [[First Presbyterian Church of Hollywood]], [[Bel Air Presbyterian Church]], [[First African Methodist Episcopal Church of Los Angeles]], [[West Angeles Church of God in Christ]], [[Second Baptist Church]], [[Crenshaw Christian Center]], [[McCarty Memorial Christian Church]], and First Congregational Church.\\n[[Image:Los Angeles Temple 1.jpg|thumb|Built in 1956, the [[Los Angeles California Temple]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] is the second largest [[Mormon]] temple in the world]]\\nThe [[Los Angeles California Temple]], the second largest [[Temple (Latter Day Saints)|temple]] operated by [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], is on [[California State Route 2|Santa Monica Boulevard]] in the [[Westwood, Los Angeles|Westwood district]] of Los Angeles. Dedicated in 1956, it was the first [[Mormon]] temple built in California and it was the largest in the world when completed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.ldschurchtemples.com\\/losangeles\\/ |title=LDS \\u2013 Los Angeles California Temple |publisher=Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints |accessdate=23 October 2011}}<\\/ref> '),
	(460, 'The Hollywood region of Los Angeles also has several significant headquarters, churches, and the [[Celebrity Center]] of [[Scientology]].'),
	(461, 'Because of Los Angeles\' large multi-ethnic population, a wide variety of faiths are practiced, including Islam, [[Buddhism]], [[Hinduism]], [[Zoroastrianism]], [[Sikhism]], [[Bah\\u00e1\'\\u00ed Faith|Bah\\u00e1\'\\u00ed]], various [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]es, [[Sufism]] and others. Immigrants from Asia for example, have formed a number of significant [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] congregations making the city home to the greatest variety of Buddhists in the world.'),
	(462, '==Economy==\\n{{further|[[Los Angeles County, California#Economy|Los Angeles County Economy]]}}\\n{{See also|Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce}}\\n[[File:Downtownplazala.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Companies such as [[US Bancorp]], [[Ernst & Young]], [[Aon Corporation|Aon]], [[Manulife Financial]], [[City National Bank (California)|City National Bank]], [[Wells Fargo]], [[Bank of America]], [[Deloitte]], [[KPMG]] and the [[Union Bank of California]] have offices in the Downtown Financial District]]\\n[[Image:L.A Financial district.JPG|thumb|The Financial District of Downtown Los Angeles]]'),
	(463, 'The economy of Los Angeles is driven by international trade, entertainment (television, motion pictures, video games, recorded music), aerospace, technology, petroleum, fashion, apparel, and tourism. Los Angeles is also the largest manufacturing center in the western United States.<ref name=\'citydata\'>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.city-data.com\\/us-cities\\/The-West\\/Los-Angeles-Economy.html|title = Los Angeles: Economy |publisher=City-data.com |accessdate=7 October 2011}}<\\/ref> The contiguous ports of Los Angeles and [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] together comprise the fifth-busiest port in the world and the most significant port in the [[Western Hemisphere]] and is vital to trade within the [[Pacific Rim]].<ref name=\'citydata\' \\/> Other significant industries include media production, finance, telecommunications, law, healthcare, and transportation. The Los Angeles-Long Beach-Santa Ana [[metropolitan statistical area]] (MSA) has a [[gross metropolitan product]] (GMP) of $735.7&nbsp;billion (as of 2010),<ref>{{cite web|title=Gross Metropolitan Product|url=http:\\/\\/greyhill.com\\/gross-metropolitan-product|publisher=Greyhill Advisors|accessdate=9 October 2011}}<\\/ref> making it the third largest economic center in the world, after the [[Greater Tokyo Area]] and the New York-Newark-Bridgeport CSA.<ref name=\\"citymayors.com\\"\\/> If counted as a country, the [[greater Los Angeles area|surrounding CSA]] has the 15<sup>th<\\/sup> largest economy in the world in terms of nominal GDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/fields\\/2195.html|title=CIA World Factbook, 2009: GDP (official exchange rate)|date=October 2008|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20081004071135\\/https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/\\/fields\\/2195.html|archivedate=4 October 2008 | accessdate = 9 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Los Angeles has been classified an \\"[[Global city|Alpha world city]]\\" according to a 2010 study by a research group at [[Loughborough University]] in England.<ref>{{cite web| url=http:\\/\\/www.lboro.ac.uk\\/gawc\\/world2010t.html| title=The World According to GaWC 2010| work=Globalization and World Cities Research Network|publisher=GaWC Loughborough University| accessdate=2 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(464, 'The city is home to seven [[Fortune 500]] companies. They are aerospace contractor [[Northrop Grumman]], energy company [[Occidental Petroleum]], healthcare provider [[Health Net]], metals distributor Reliance Steel & Aluminum, engineering firm [[AECOM]], real estate group [[CBRE Group]] and builder [[Tutor Perini]].'),
	(465, 'Other companies headquartered in Los Angeles include [[California Pizza Kitchen]], [[The Capital Group Companies|Capital Group]], [[Capstone Turbine]], [[Cathay Bank]], [[City National Bank (California)|City National Bank]], [[The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf]], [[DeviantArt]], [[Far East National Bank]], [[Farmers Insurance Group]], [[Fox Entertainment Group]], [[Gibson, Dunn & Crutcher]], [[Guess (clothing)|Guess?]], [[Hanmi Bank]], [[Herbalife]], [[J2 Global Communications]], [[The Jim Henson Company]], [[KB Home]], [[Korn\\/Ferry]], [[Latham & Watkins]], [[Mercury Insurance Group]], [[Oaktree Capital Management]], [[O\\u2019Melveny & Myers]]; [[Paul, Hastings, Janofsky & Walker]], [[Premier America]], [[Premiere Radio Networks]], [[Rentech]], [[Roll International]], [[Sunkist Growers, Incorporated|Sunkist]], [[TCW Group|The TCW Group]], [[Tokyopop]], [[Triton Media Group]], [[United Online]], and [[VCA Antech]].'),
	(466, 'The [[University of Southern California]] (USC) is the city\'s largest [[private sector]] employer and contributes $4&nbsp;billion annually to the local economy.<ref>{{cite news|first=Evan |last=George|url=http:\\/\\/www.downtownnews.com\\/articles\\/2006\\/12\\/11\\/news\\/news05.txt |title=Trojan Dollars: Study Finds USC Worth $4&nbsp;Billion Annually to L.A. County|work=Los Angeles Downtown News|date=December 11, 2006|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20090430211002\\/http:\\/\\/www.downtownnews.com\\/articles\\/2006\\/12\\/11\\/news\\/news05.txt |archivedate=April 30, 2009}}<\\/ref>'),
	(467, 'According to the city\'s 2010 Comprehensive Annual Financial Report, the top ten employers in the city as of 2009 are, in descending order, the City of Los Angeles, the [[Los Angeles County, California|County of Los Angeles]], [[University of California, Los Angeles]], [[University of Southern California]], [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]], [[Kaiser Permanente]], [[Fox Entertainment Group]], [[Farmers Insurance Group]], TeamOne,and [[Northrop Grumman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/ens.lacity.org\\/ctr\\/financial\\/ctrfinancial18265184_02262010.pdf |title=City of Los Angeles CAFR|format=PDF |accessdate=14 October 2011|page=332 (367)}}<\\/ref>'),
	(468, '==Education==\\n===Colleges and universities===\\n[[Image:UCLA-old-statenormal-campus.jpg|thumb|left|Second branch of the [[California State Normal School]] in downtown Los Angeles opened its doors in 1882.]]\\nThere are three public universities located within the city limits: [[California State University, Los Angeles]] (CSULA), [[California State University, Northridge]] (CSUN) and [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA).\\nPrivate colleges in the city include the [[AFI Conservatory|American Film Institute Conservatory]], [[Alliant International University]], [[Syracuse University]] (Los Angeles Campus), [[American InterContinental University Los Angeles Campus|American InterContinental University]], [[American Jewish University]], [[American Musical and Dramatic Academy|The American Musical and Dramatic Academy \\u2013 Los Angeles campus]], [[Antioch University]]\'s Los Angeles campus, [[Charles R. Drew University of Medicine and Science]], [[Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising]]\'s Los Angeles campus (FIDM), [[Los Angeles Film School]], [[Loyola Marymount University]] (LMU is also the parent university of [[Loyola Law School]] located in Los Angeles), [[Marymount College, Palos Verdes|Marymount College]], [[Mount St. Mary\'s College]], [[National University (California)|National University]] of California, [[Occidental College]] (\\"Oxy\\"), [[Otis College of Art and Design]] (Otis), [[Southern California Institute of Architecture]] (SCI-Arc), [[Southwestern Law School]], and [[University of Southern California]] (USC).'),
	(469, 'The community college system consists of nine campuses governed by the trustees of the Los Angeles Community College District: [[East Los Angeles College]] (ELAC), [[Los Angeles City College]] (LACC), [[Los Angeles Harbor College]], [[Los Angeles Mission College]], [[Los Angeles Pierce College]], [[Los Angeles Valley College]] (LAVC), [[Los Angeles Southwest College]], [[Los Angeles Trade-Technical College]] and [[West Los Angeles College]].'),
	(470, '===Schools and libraries===\\n[[File:Los-angeles-central-library.jpg|thumb|The Los Angeles Central Library in Downtown Los Angeles]]\\n{{See also|Los Angeles County, California#Colleges and universities|List of high schools in Los Angeles County, California}}\\n[[Los Angeles Unified School District]] serves almost all of the city of Los Angeles, as well as several surrounding communities, with a student population around 800,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.census.gov\\/hhes\\/www\\/saipe\\/district.html |title=US Census, District information |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> After [[California Proposition 13 (1978)|Proposition 13]] was approved in 1978, urban school districts had considerable trouble with funding. LAUSD has become known for its underfunded, overcrowded and poorly maintained campuses, although its 162 [[Magnet school]]s help compete with local private schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/media.www.dailytrojan.com\\/media\\/storage\\/paper679\\/news\\/2005\\/01\\/26\\/News\\/Magnet.Schools.Just.As.Competitive.As.Private.Schools-841415.shtml |title=Magnet schools just as competitive as private schools|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20070504032306\\/http:\\/\\/media.www.dailytrojan.com\\/media\\/storage\\/paper679\\/news\\/2005\\/01\\/26\\/News\\/Magnet.Schools.Just.As.Competitive.As.Private.Schools-841415.shtml |archivedate=4 May 2007 | accessdate = 24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Several small sections of Los Angeles are in the [[Las Virgenes Unified School District]]. Los Angeles County Office of Education operates the [[Los Angeles County High School for the Arts]]. The [[Los Angeles Public Library]] system operates 72 public libraries in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.lapl.org\\/branches\\/ |title=LA Public Library |publisher=Lapl.org |accessdate=24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Enclaves of unincorporated areas are served by the [[County of Los Angeles Public Library]], many are within walking distance to City of Los Angeles residents.'),
	(471, 'The city and the rest of the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]] are served by an extensive network of freeways and highways. The [[Texas Transportation Institute]], which publishes an annual Urban Mobility Report, ranked Los Angeles road traffic as the most congested in the United States in 2005 as measured by annual delay per traveler.<ref>{{cite news | url = http:\\/\\/www.forbes.com\\/2008\\/04\\/24\\/cities-commute-fuel-forbeslife-cx_mw_0424realestate.html | title = Best And Worst Cities For Commuters | last = Woolsey | first = Matt | date = 25 April 2008 | accessdate = 24 October 2011 | work=Forbes}}<\\/ref> The average traveler in Los Angeles experienced 72 hours of traffic delay per year according to the study. Los Angeles was followed by San Francisco\\/[[Oakland]], Washington, D.C. and [[Atlanta]], (each with 60 hours of delay).<ref>{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/www.forbes.com\\/2008\\/04\\/24\\/cities-commute-fuel-forbeslife-cx_mw_0424realestate3_slide_3.html?thisSpeed=undefined | title = In Depth: 10 Worst Cities For Commuters | publisher = Forbes Magazine | last = Woolsey | first = Matt | accessdate = 24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Despite the congestion in the city, the mean travel time for commuters in Los Angeles is shorter than other major cities, including New York City, [[Philadelphia]] and Chicago. Los Angeles\' mean travel time for work commutes in 2006 was 29.2 minutes, similar to those of San Francisco and Washington, D.C.<ref name=\\"ACS2006\\">{{cite web|title=American Community Survey 2006, Table S0802|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|url=http:\\/\\/factfinder.census.gov\\/servlet\\/DCGeoSelectServlet?ds_name=ACS_2006_EST_G00_}}{{dead link | date = October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(472, 'Among the major highways that connect LA to the rest of the nation include [[Interstate 5]], which runs south through San Diego to [[Tijuana]] in Mexico and then north to the [[Canada \\u2013 United States border|Canadian border]] through [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], and [[Seattle]]; [[Interstate 10]], the southernmost east\\u2013west, coast-to-coast [[Interstate Highway]] in the United States, going to [[Jacksonville, Florida]]; and [[U.S. Route 101]], which heads to the [[California Central Coast]], San Francisco, the [[Redwood Empire]], and the [[Oregon]] and [[Washington (U.S. State)|Washington]] coasts.'),
	(473, '===Transit systems===\\n[[File:Los angeles metro existing and under construction 2009.png|thumb|Current [[Los Angeles County Metro Rail|Los Angeles Metro Rail]] map showing existing and under-construction lines.]]'),
	(474, 'The [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] and other agencies operate an extensive system of bus lines, as well as [[Rapid transit|subway]] and light rail lines across Los Angeles County, with a combined monthly ridership (measured in individual boardings) of 38.8&nbsp;million as of September, 2011. The majority of this (30.5&nbsp;million) is taken up by the city\'s bus system,<ref name=metro>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.metro.net\\/news\\/pages\\/ridership-statistics\\/ | publisher = Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority | title = Ridership Statistics | accessdate = 24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> the second busiest in the country. The subway and light rail combined average the remaining roughly 8.2&nbsp;million boardings per month.<ref name=metro \\/> In 2005, 10.2% of Los Angeles commuters rode some form of public transportation.<ref>{{cite news| url = http:\\/\\/money.cnn.com\\/2007\\/06\\/13\\/real_estate\\/public_transit_commutes\\/index.htm| title = New Yorkers are Top Transit Users| accessdate =24 October 2011| first=Les|last= Christie| date = 29 June 2007| publisher=Cable News Network}}<\\/ref>'),
	(475, 'The city\'s subway system is the [[List of United States rapid transit systems by ridership|ninth busiest in the United States]] and its light rail system is the country\'s [[List of United States light rail systems by ridership|second busiest]].<ref name=APTA>{{cite web | publisher = American Public Transportation Association|url=http:\\/\\/www.apta.com\\/resources\\/statistics\\/Documents\\/Ridership\\/2011_q1_ridership_APTA.pdf|title= Public Transit Ridership Report|date= First Quarter 2011|accessdate=24 October 2011}}<\\/ref> The rail system includes the [[Red Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Red]] and [[Purple Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Purple]] subway lines, as well as the [[Gold Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Gold]], [[Blue Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Blue]], and [[Green Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Green]] light rail lines. The first phase of the [[Expo Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Expo Line]] is scheduled to open in November 2011. The [[Metro Orange Line]] is a [[bus rapid transit]] line with stops and frequency similar to those of a light rail. The city is also central to the [[commuter rail]] system [[Metrolink (Southern California)|Metrolink]], which links Los Angeles to all neighboring counties as well as many suburbs.'),
	(476, 'Besides the rail service provided by Metrolink and the Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority, Los Angeles is served by inter-city passenger trains from [[Amtrak]]. The main rail station in the city is [[Union Station (Los Angeles)|Union Station]] just north of Downtown.'),
	(477, '===Airports===\\n[[Image:LAX LA.jpg|thumb|The Theme Building at LAX]]\\nThe main Los Angeles airport is [[Los Angeles International Airport]] {{airport codes|LAX|KLAX}}. The sixth busiest commercial airport in the world and the third busiest in the United States, LAX handled over 61&nbsp;million passengers and 2&nbsp;million tons of cargo in 2006. LAX is a hub for [[United Airlines]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.united.com\\/page\\/article\\/0,6722,52124,00.html |title=United Airlines \\u2013 Vacation Planning at United.com: Visit Los Angeles |publisher=United.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(478, 'Other major nearby commercial airports include:\\n* {{airport codes|ONT|KONT}} [[LA\\/Ontario International Airport]], owned by the city of Los Angeles; serves the Inland Empire.\\n* {{airport codes|BUR|KBUR}} [[Bob Hope Airport]], formerly known as \'\'Burbank Airport\'\'; serves the San Fernando and San Gabriel Valleys\\n* {{airport codes|LGB|KLGB}} [[Long Beach Airport]], serves the Long Beach\\/Harbor area\\n* {{airport codes|SNA|KSNA}} [[John Wayne Airport]] of Orange County.\\n* {{airport codes|PMD|KPMD}} [[LA\\/Palmdale Regional Airport]] is owned by the city of Los Angeles and serves the northern outlying communities of the [[Santa Clarita Valley|Santa Clarita]] and [[Antelope Valley]]s.'),
	(479, 'One of the world\'s busiest general-aviation airport is also located in Los Angeles, [[Van Nuys Airport]] {{airport codes|VNY|KVNY}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.lawa.org\\/welcome_VNY.aspx?id=92 |title=Van Nuys Airport General Description |publisher=Los Angeles World Airports |accessdate=25 October 2011}}<\\/ref>'),
	(480, '===Seaports===\\n[[Image:Los Angeles Bridge.jpg|thumb|A view of the [[Vincent Thomas Bridge]] reaching Terminal Island]]'),
	(481, 'The [[Port of Los Angeles]] is located in [[San Pedro Bay (California)|San Pedro Bay]] in the [[San Pedro, Los Angeles|San Pedro]] neighborhood, approximately {{convert|20|mi|km}} south of Downtown. Also called Los Angeles Harbor and WORLDPORT LA, the port complex occupies {{convert|7500|acre|km2}} of land and water along {{convert|43|mi|km}} of waterfront. It adjoins the separate [[Port of Long Beach]].'),
	(482, 'The sea ports of the [[Port of Los Angeles]] and [[Port of Long Beach]] together make up the \'\'Los Angeles\\/Long Beach Harbor\'\'.<ref>[http:\\/\\/www.portoflosangeles.org\\/facilities\\/pilot_station.asp Facilities] \\u2013 The Port of Los Angeles site<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.mxsocal.org\\/pdffiles\\/108th%20HSC%20Mtg%20Apr%205%202006.pdf |title=Los Angeles\\/Long Beach Harbor Safety Committee |format=PDF |accessdate=March 16, 2011}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.harboremployers.com\\/web\\/ |title=Los Angeles\\/Long Beach Harbor Employers Association |publisher=Harboremployers.com |accessdate=March 16, 2011}}<\\/ref> Both ports is the 5th busiest [[Container (cargo)|container]] port in the World, with a trade volume of over 14.2&nbsp;million [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU\'s]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/aapa.files.cms-plus.com\\/Statistics\\/WORLD%20PORT%20RANKINGS%2020081.pdf |title=AAPA World Port Rankings 2008 |format=PDF |accessdate=March 16, 2011}}<\\/ref> Singly, the Port of Los Angeles is the busiest container port in the United States and the largest cruise ship center on the [[West Coast of the United States]] \\u2013 Port\'s World Cruise Center serves about 800,000 passengers in 2009.<ref>[http:\\/\\/www.portoflosangeles.org\\/about\\/faqs.asp#9 About the Port] \\u2013 The Port of Los Angeles site<\\/ref>'),
	(483, 'The port includes four bridges: the [[Vincent Thomas Bridge]], [[Henry Ford Bridge]], [[Gerald Desmond Bridge]], and [[Commodore Schuyler F. Heim Bridge]].'),
	(484, '==Demographics==\\n{{Main|Demographics of Los Angeles}}\\n[[Image:Los Angeles, CA from the air.jpg|thumb|240px|A view of downtown Los Angeles from the air.]]\\n{{Historical populations\\n|type=USA\\n|1850|1610\\n|1860|4385\\n|1870|5728\\n|1880|11183\\n|1890|50395\\n|1900|102479\\n|1910|319198\\n|1920|576673\\n|1930|1238048\\n|1940|1504277\\n|1950|1970358\\n|1960|2479015\\n|1970|2816061\\n|1980|2966850\\n|1990|3485398\\n|2000|3694820\\n|2010|3792621\\n| footnote=source:<ref>{{cite book|last=Moffatt|first=Riley|title=Population History of Western U.S. Cities & Towns, 1850\\u20131990|location=Lanham, Maryland|publisher=Scarecrow|year=1996|page=41}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http:\\/\\/www.census.gov\\/popest\\/cities\\/tables\\/SUB-EST2009-01.csv | title = Annual Estimates of the Resident Population for Incorporated Places Over 100,000, Ranked by July&nbsp;1, 2009 Population: April 1, 2000 to July 1, 2009| format = [[comma-separated values|CSV]] | publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division | date = July 1, 2009 | accessdate =June 28, 2010}}<\\/ref>\\n|}}'),
	(485, 'The [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{USCensus-2010CA}}<\\/ref> reported that Los Angeles had a population of 3,792,621.<ref name=\\"Census 2010, LA city\\">{{cite web |url=http:\\/\\/quickfacts.census.gov\\/qfd\\/states\\/06\\/0644000.html |title=Los Angeles (city), California |work=State & County QuickFacts |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}<\\/ref> The population density was 7,544.6 people per square mile (2,913.0\\/km\\u00b2). The racial makeup of Los Angeles was 1,888,158 (49.8%) [[White American|White]], 365,118 (9.6%) African American, 28,215 (0.7%) Native American, 426,959 (11.3%) [[Asian American|Asian]] (3.2% [[Filipino American|Filipino]], 2.9% [[Korean American|Korean]], 1.8% [[Chinese American|Chinese]], 0.9% [[Indian American|Indian]], 0.9% [[Japanese American|Japanese]], 0.5% [[Vietnamese American|Vietnamese]], 0.3% [[Thai American|Thai]], 0.1% [[Cambodian American|Cambodian]]), 5,577 (0.1%) [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander]], 902,959 (23.8%) from [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census#Race|other races]], and 175,635 (4.6%) from [[Multiracial American|two or more races]].<ref name=\\"Census 2010, LA city\\"\\/> '),
	(486, '[[Non-Hispanic whites]] were 28.7% of the population in 2010.<ref name=\\"Census 2010, LA city\\"\\/> [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanics or Latinos]] of any race were 1,838,822 persons (48.5%).<ref name=\\"Census 2010, LA city\\"\\/> Among the Hispanic population, 31.9% are [[Mexican American|Mexican]], 6.0% [[Salvadoran American|Salvadoran]], 3.6% [[Guatemalan American|Guatemalan]], 0.6% [[Honduran American|Honduran]], 0.4% [[Nicaraguan American|Nicaraguan]], 0.4% [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]], 0.4% [[Peruvian American|Peruvian]], 0.4% [[Cuban American|Cuban]], 0.3% [[Colombian American|Colombian]], 0.2% Argentinean, and 0.2% Ecuadorian.  '),
	(487, '* [[German American|German]]: 4.5% (170,483)\\n* [[Irish American|Irish]]: 3.9% (146,658)\\n* [[English American|English]]: 3.5% (129,684)\\n* [[Italian American|Italian]]: 2.8% (100,145)\\n* [[Russian American|Russian]]: 2.6% (98,737)\\n* [[Polish American|Polish]]: 1.6% (59,774)\\n* [[French American|French]]: 1.2% (45,127)\\n* [[Scottish American|Scottish]]: 0.8% (28,931)\\n* [[Swedish American|Swedish]]: 0.6% (23,227)\\n* [[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]]: 0.6% (22,651)'),
	(488, 'Los Angeles is home to people from more than 140 countries speaking 224 different identified languages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http:\\/\\/www.lacity.org\\/mayor\\/deliveringresults\\/results_cibasic.htm |title=City basics |publisher=Lacity.org |date=April 12, 2005 |accessdate=April 13, 2010}}<\\/ref> Ethnic enclaves like [[Chinatown, Los Angeles|Chinatown]], [[Historic Filipinotown, Los Angeles|Historic Filipinotown]], [[Koreatown]], [[Little Armenia, Los Angeles|Little Armenia]], [[Little Ethiopia, Los Angeles|Little Ethiopia]], [[Tehrangeles]], [[Little Tokyo, Los Angeles|Little Tokyo]], and [[Thai Town, Los Angeles|Thai Town]] provide examples of the [[Multilingualism|polyglot]] character of Los Angeles.'),
	(489, '==Law and government==\\n{{See also|List of elected officials in Los Angeles}}\\nThe city is governed by a [[Mayor-council government|mayor-council]] system. The current [[Mayor of Los Angeles|mayor]] is [[Antonio Villaraigosa]]. There are 15 [[Los Angeles City Council|city council]] districts. Other elected city officials include the City Attorney [[Carmen Trutanich]] and the City Controller [[Wendy Greuel]]. The city attorney prosecutes misdemeanors within the city limits. The district attorney, elected by county voters, prosecutes misdemeanors in unincorporated areas and in 78 of the 88 cities in the county, as well as felonies throughout the county.'),
	(490, 'The [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) polices the city of Los Angeles, but the city also maintains four specialized police agencies; The Office of Public Safety, within the General Services Department (which is responsible for security and law enforcement services at city facilities, including City Hall, city parks and libraries, [[Los Angeles Zoo|the Los Angeles Zoo]], and the Convention Center), the Port Police, within the Harbor Department (which is responsible for land, air and sea law enforcement services at the Port of Los Angeles), the Los Angeles City Schools Police department which handles law enforcement for all city schools, and the Airport Police, within the [[Los Angeles World Airports]] Department (which is responsible for law enforcement services at all four city-owned airports, including [[Los Angeles International Airport]] (LAX), [[LA\\/Ontario International Airport]] (ONT), [[LA\\/Palmdale Regional Airport]] (PMD), and [[Van Nuys Airport]] (VNY).'),
	(491, '===Environmental issues===\\nThe name given by the [[Chumash people|Chumash]] tribe of Native Americans for the area now known as Los Angeles translates to \\"the valley of smoke.\\"<ref>According to Gordon J. MacDonald, geophysicist and professor formerly with the [[University of California, San Diego]], quoted in {{cite news|first=Chris |last=Bowman |archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20080709015204\\/http:\\/\\/www.sacbee.com\\/101\\/story\\/1066675.html|url=http:\\/\\/www.sacbee.com\\/101\\/story\\/1066675.html|title=Smoke is Normal \\u2013 for 1800|work=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=8 July 2008|archivedate=9 July 2008|accessdate = 6 October 2011}}<\\/ref> Owing to geography, heavy reliance on automobiles, and the Los Angeles\\/Long Beach port complex, Los Angeles suffers from air pollution in the form of smog. The [[Los Angeles Basin]] and the San Fernando Valley are susceptible to [[inversion (meteorology)|atmospheric inversion]], which holds in the exhausts from road vehicles, airplanes, locomotives, shipping, manufacturing, and other sources.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stimson|first=Thomas E.|title=What can we do about smog?|url=http:\\/\\/books.google.com\\/books?id=xdwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA65|accessdate=6 October 2011|date=July 1955|publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]]|page=65|issn=00324558}}<\\/ref> The smog season lasts from May to October.<ref name=\\"Information1983\\">{{cite book|title=Smog Hangs Over Olympic Athletes|url=http:\\/\\/books.google.com\\/books?id=CJNJjq8h2zwC&pg=PA393|accessdate=6 October 2011|date=11 August 1983|publisher=New Scientist|page=393|issn=02624079}}<\\/ref> Unlike other large cities that rely on rain to clear smog, Los Angeles gets only {{convert|15|in|mm|-1}} of rain each year: pollution accumulates over many consecutive days. Issues of air quality in Los Angeles and other major cities led to the passage of early national environmental legislation, including the [[United States Clean Air Act|Clean Air Act]]. More recently, the state of California has led the nation in working to limit pollution by mandating [[low-emission vehicle]]s. Smog is expected to continue to drop in the coming years due to aggressive steps to reduce it, [[Electric car|electric]] and [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] cars, improvements in mass transit, and other pollution reducing measures.'),
	(492, 'The number of Stage 1 smog alerts in Los Angeles has declined from over 100 per year in the 1970s to almost zero in the new millennium. Despite improvement, the 2006 and 2007 annual reports of the [[American Lung Association]] ranked the city as the most polluted in the country with short-term particle pollution and year-round particle pollution.<ref name=\\"shortTermPollutedCities\\">{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/lungaction.org\\/reports\\/sota06_table2.html |title=People at Risk In 25 U.S. Cities Most Polluted by Short-Term Particle Pollution|publisher=[[American Lung Association]]|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20070325171724\\/http:\\/\\/lungaction.org\\/reports\\/sota06_table2a.html|archivedate=25 March 2007|accessdate = 7 October 2011}}<\\/ref> In 2008, the city was ranked the second most polluted and again had the highest year-round particulate pollution.<ref>{{cite web|title= Pittsburgh and Los Angeles the most polluted US cities|url=http:\\/\\/www.citymayors.com\\/environment\\/polluted_uscities.html|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20080912203013\\/http:\\/\\/citymayors.com\\/environment\\/polluted_uscities.html|archivedate=12 September 2008|date= 4 May 2008|publisher=citymayors.com | accessdate = 7 October 2011}}<\\/ref> In addition, the [[groundwater]] is increasingly threatened by [[Methyl tert-butyl ether|MTBE]] from [[filling station|gas stations]] and [[perchlorate]] from [[rocket propellant|rocket fuel]]. With pollution still a significant problem, the city continues to take aggressive steps to improve air and water conditions.<ref>{{cite web|first=Theresa Adams|url=http:\\/\\/www.portoflosangeles.org\\/Press\\/REL_Air_Quality_Update_2-16-06.pdf|title= Air Quality Programs at the Port of Los Angeles saw Refinement in 2005 with Focus on Ramping up in 2006|publisher=Port of Los Angeles (News Release)|date=February 17, 2006|accessdate=September 29, 2011|unused_data=;ast=Lopez}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|url=http:\\/\\/www.environmentaldefense.org\\/article.cfm?ContentID=4180|title=Air Quality Protections Take Off|date=December 6, 2004|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20060301030820\\/http:\\/\\/www.environmentaldefense.org\\/article.cfm?ContentID=4180|archivedate=March 1, 2006|publisher=Environmental Defense}}<\\/ref> The city met its goal of providing 20 percent of the city\'s power from renewable sources in 2010.<ref name=\\"Renewable Energy\\">{{cite news|url=http:\\/\\/www.bloomberg.com\\/news\\/2011-01-14\\/los-angeles-meets-20-percent-renewable-energy-goal.html |title=Los Angeles meets 20 percent renewable energy goal |publisher=Bloomberg|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20110201090303\\/http:\\/\\/www.bloomberg.com\\/news\\/2011-01-14\\/los-angeles-meets-20-percent-renewable-energy-goal.html|archivedate=1 February 2011|date=14 January 2011|accessdate = 7 October 2011}}<\\/ref>\\n[[Image:Los Angeles Pollution.jpg|thumb|center|500px|A view of Los Angeles covered in smog]]'),
	(493, '===Neighborhood councils===\\n[[Image:Bunker Hill Downtown Los Angeles.jpg|thumb|[[Bunker Hill, Los Angeles|Bunker Hill]] in L.A.]]\\nVoters created [[Neighborhood Councils]] in the Charter Reform of 1999. First proposed by City Council member [[Joel Wachs]] in 1996, they were designed to promote public participation in government and make it more responsive to local needs.'),
	(494, 'The councils are official government bodies and so their governing bodies and committees must abide by California\'s [[Brown Act]], which governs the meetings of deliberative assemblies.'),
	(495, 'The first notable concern of the neighborhood councils collectively was the opposition by some of them in March 2004 to an 18% increase in water rates by the city\'s [[Los Angeles Department of Water and Power|Department of Water and Power]]. This led the City Council to approve only a limited increase pending independent review. More recently, some of the councils petitioned the City Council in summer 2006 to allow them to introduce ideas for legislative action, but the City Council put off a decision.'),
	(496, '===Crime===\\n{{See also|Crime in Los Angeles}}\\n[[Image:May Day Immigration March LA66.jpg|thumb|The [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]] during May Day 2006 in front of the new Caltrans District 7 Headquarters]]\\nLike [[Crime in the United States|most American cities]], Los Angeles has been experiencing significant decline in crime since the mid-1990s, and reached a 50-year low in 2009 with 314 homicides.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http:\\/\\/www.wavenewspapers.com\\/news\\/local\\/northeast-edition\\/80935317.html |agency=Wire services |title=Crime rate lowest in 50 years, LAPD says |newspaper=Los Angeles Wave |date=January 10, 2010 |accessdate=April 14, 2010}}  Northeast Edition.<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.lapdonline.org\\/read_the_beat_magazine\\/pdf_view\\/43819 |title=LAPD year-end crime statistics |accessdate=April 13, 2010}}<\\/ref> [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] is a member of the [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http:\\/\\/www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org\\/html\\/about\\/members.shtml| title=Mayors Against Illegal Guns: Coalition Members|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20070703052727\\/http:\\/\\/www.mayorsagainstillegalguns.org\\/html\\/about\\/members.shtml|archivedate=July 3, 2007}}<\\/ref>'),
	(497, 'The [[Los Angeles crime family]] dominated organized crime in the city during the [[Prohibition in the United States|Prohibition era]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/mafia.z04.org.ua\\/zPage_48.html |title=The Mafia Encyclopedia. mafia \\u043c\\u0430\\u0448\\u0438\\u043d\\u044b. three 6 mafia. \\u0442\\u0440\\u0435\\u043d\\u0435\\u0440 mafia |publisher=Mafia.z04.org.ua |date=November 12, 1926 |accessdate=April 13, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=September 2011}}<\\/ref> and reached its peak during the 1940s and 1950s as part of the [[American Mafia]] but has gradually declined since then with the rise of various black and [[Hispanic]] gangs.'),
	(498, 'According to the Los Angeles Police Department, the city is home to 26,000 gang members, organized into 250 gangs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http:\\/\\/www.lapdonline.org\\/get_informed\\/content_basic_view\\/1396 |title=Los Angeles Police Department Gang subsite |publisher=Lapdonline.org |accessdate=April 13, 2010}}<\\/ref> Among them are the [[Crips]], [[Bloods]], [[Sure\\u00f1os]], [[Mara Salvatrucha]] and [[18th Street gang|18th Street]]. This has led to the city being referred to as the \\"Gang Capital of America\\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.alertnet.org\\/thenews\\/newsdesk\\/N08492271.htm|title=Police target 11 worst Los Angeles street gangs|publisher=Reuters AlertNet|archiveurl=http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20080218003406\\/http:\\/\\/www.alertnet.org\\/thenews\\/newsdesk\\/N08492271.htm |archivedate=February 18, 2008}}<\\/ref>'),
	(499, '==Sister cities==\\n<!--\\n *** IMPORTANT ***\\n * Please do not add or remove sister cities unless you provide a reliable *\\n * source. This list is verified by http:\\/\\/www.lacity.org\\/SisterCities\\/, *\\n * which lists 25 sister cities. If you make changes to this list without *\\n * citing a source, your edits will be reverted. *\\n-->\\n[[Image:Los Angeles City Hall with sister cities 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|A sign near [[Los Angeles City Hall|City Hall]] points to the sister cities of Los Angeles]]\\nLos Angeles has 25 [[sister cities]],<ref name=Sistercities>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/sistercities.lacity.org\\/ |title=Sister Cities of Los Angeles|publisher=sistercities.lacity.org|accessdate=September 29, 2011}}<\\/ref> listed chronologically by year joined:\\n{{Colbegin}}\\n*{{flagicon|ISR}} [[Eilat]], Israel (1959)\\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Nagoya]], Japan (1959)\\n*{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Bahia, Brazil (1962)\\n*{{flagicon|PAK}} [[Faisalabad]], Pakistan (2009)\\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Bordeaux]], France (1964)\\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Berlin]], Germany (1967)\\n*{{flagicon|ZMB}} [[Lusaka]], Zambia (1968)\\n*{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Mexico City]], Mexico (1969)\\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Auckland City]], New Zealand (1971)\\n*{{flagicon|KOR}} [[Busan]], South Korea (1971)\\n*{{flagicon|IND}} [[Mumbai]], Maharashtra, India (1972)\\n*{{flagicon|IRN}} [[Tehran]], Iran (1972)\\n*{{flagicon|TWN}} [[Taipei]], Taiwan, Republic of China (1979)\\n*{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Guangzhou]], People\'s Republic of China (1981)\\n*{{flagicon|GRE}} [[Athens]], Greece (1984)\\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia (1984)\\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada (1986)\\n*{{flagicon|EGY}} [[Giza]], Egypt (1989)\\n*{{flagicon|IDN}} [[Jakarta]], Indonesia (1990)\\n*{{flagicon|LTU}} [[Kaunas]], Lithuania (1991)\\n*{{flagicon|PHL}} [[Makati]], Philippines (1992)\\n*{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Split (city)|Split]], Croatia (1993)\\n*{{flagicon|SLV}} [[San Salvador]], El Salvador (2005)\\n*{{flagicon|LBN}} [[Beirut]], Lebanon (2006)\\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Ischia]], Campania, Italy (2006)\\n*{{flagicon|ARM}} [[Yerevan]], Armenia (2007)\\n{{Colend}}'),
	(500, '* {{flagicon|ISR}} Los Angeles also has an exchange partnership with [[Tel Aviv]], Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/www.jewishla.org\\/Tel_Aviv_LA_Partnership.cfm|title=Tel Aviv\\/Los Angeles Partnership|year=2007|publisher=The Jewish Federation of Greater Los Angeles|accessdate=August 7, 2008 |archiveurl = http:\\/\\/web.archive.org\\/web\\/20080623075353\\/http:\\/\\/www.jewishla.org\\/Tel_Aviv_LA_Partnership.cfm |archivedate = June 23, 2008}}<\\/ref>'),
	(501, 'In addition, Los Angeles has the following \\"friendship cities\\".<ref name=\\"Manchester\\">{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/menmedia.co.uk\\/manchestereveningnews\\/news\\/s\\/1128076_twinning_link_with_la|title=Twinning link with LA|publisher=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=July 28, 2009}}<\\/ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http:\\/\\/sistercitiesofla.com\\/|title=Sister cities of Los Angeles, Inc|year=2010|accessdate=February 8, 2010}}<\\/ref>:\\n*{{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]] and [[Manchester]], England, United Kingdom\\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[\\u0141\\u00f3d\\u017a]], Poland'),
